    "The convexity of both f (x) and K implies that the feasible set is convex and closed.",
    "Hence, the solution x ⋆ obtained by the solver corresponds to a global minimum.",
    "This property contrasts sharply with non-convex or neural approaches that may converge to suboptimal local minima.In our conic maximization problem, b ∈ R m and c ∈ R n denote the data vectors, y is the dual variable, and the dual cone of R n × K is {0} n × K *.",
    "Since both K * and the dual objective f (y) are convex, the optimal solution y ⋆ is a global maximizer.Based on the properties established above, and by invoking Slater's condition [9], the existence of a strictly feasible point guarantees that strong duality holds.",
    "Therefore,p ⋆ = d ⋆,(5)where p ⋆ and d ⋆ denote the primal and dual optimal values."
